description:
The crowning glory of my former PhD field site of Ulu Geroh is none other than the parasitic flower, Rafflesia cantleyii. 
The plant is an ephemeral beauty, spending up to 9 months as a relatively inconspicuous bud attached to its host plant before blossoming into one of the largest flower in the world, which lasts for less than a week.

description:
Saw this Rafflesia flowers in the forest up in the hills on property owned by local farmers.

First pic shows a newly bloomed flower as the farmer has been checking on them everyday and that morning, he informed us of the full bloom so that we can visit.

There were more than 10 other buds of the Rafflesia of different stages.  Pic#3 shows a new bud and Pic#2 is a later stage bud of around 5 months old.

According to the farmer, it takes around 9 months for the flower to fully bloom and it last 5-7 days only.
